With experience we learn to celebrate all the tiny victories. I discovered that I have a neurodivergent brain that made it difficult for me to adapt to a big change in my life. With the right help and attitude the wheels catch momentum. My thesis is moving guys! #ADHDvictory

I was told that my 30s would be transcendental. Little did I suspect that that meant destroying the old and building something new from it. Progress and power may sometimes require unwilling sacrifice but once you start yielding rewards, it feels worth it.

We all seek power. We all seek to have some control over situation and outcomes. Power is more than strength. It comes from the people we surround ourselves with. With the skills we learn. From having an income. By surpassing challenges. Even from something as simple as belief.

Haven't you noticed? Above many other things we desire the feeling of progress. It doesn't have to be progress itself but just the idea. That's why we clean our desks when we have to study. That's why we go on a crisis around 25 and/or 50. Feeling stuck destroys us.

We are damn lucky... let's not sleep on it.

Those of us coming from a western country that is used to peace and freedom are fools to believe that none of these things could ever happen in our land. I think that we have seen in the past years how delicate the balance of peace and freedom is.

The events happening now in Ukraine are heart-breaking. I cannot stop thinking on how this will only produce more gut-wrenching stories while people lose their homes, their loved ones and all kinds of securities. Those that escape will not necessarily find security elsewhere.

Coming across all these stories have been seriously humbling. I am damn privileged. Privileged to have a skin color that doesn't make me a target racism. To be in a country where my sexuality can be expressed openly. Lucky to be able to return home if I please. Damn lucky.
I've met people from Sri Lanka that talked to me about genocides and ongoing civil conflicts.
I have met people from Palestina and they tell me the gut wrenching experience of finding their brother beheaded during the current conflicts...
I have met people from Syria and tells me the ventures they undertake to see their family in other countries to avoid getting caught again in ongoing conflicts.
I have met people who escaped to Belgium to avoid political turmoil in Venezuela. Hearing the stories of how they managed to survive and escape makes you think on how lucky a lot of us are.

Being in Belgium has been humbling. I have met a lot of people who came here to survive crushing conflicts in their home countries. I used to complain that I had not visited my country in 3 years... while here many people will never see their homes again...

Perhaps, this mechanic could throw in a conversation prompt or two about a particular topic to kick start the conversation. I think the initiative of Tandem is amazing and it does provide a great way to connect native speakers and learners even from opposite sides of the world.

My main goal is to practice the language with a native speakers regardless of who they are (how they look like or their age). So I have a suggestion, what if there was a die roll tool that would connect you to another random online user native in the language you wanna learn.

One comment I keep seeing online is that a lot of people use it as a Tinder. I think there is a strong need to make a profile interesting enough to get people to talk to you but it feels as if there needs to be a mechanic that pushes people to connect and engage in conversation.

The best way to learn a language is to put it to practice. Practicing with my classmates for a short 5mins two days a week is not enough. @TandemAppHQ offers a great opportunity to practice the language with willing native speakers.

I just wanted to share my experience; maybe this will help someone else. Ever since I suspected ADHD I adopted a lot of helpful habits and self compassion. My painful anxiety is gone. My procrastination has decreased. Now with ADHD meds I can get my stuff done. I am confident 🙃.

A diagnosis does help with a well-needed validation. Yes, everyone procrastinates and can have troubles focusing at times but is it affecting your life to the degree that your career and relationships are in peril? Its hard to explain to people without receiving some gaslighting.

I learned that ADHD is much more complex than the stereotype we are taught through media. Did you know that ADHDers can hyperfocus?! Woot! By learning how my brain works I learned to have compassion for myself and stop beating my self-worth whenever I didnt follow through.

It's been two weeks now that I have been using ADHD medication for my inattention. The joy that I feel is unmeasurable. I get goosebumps every time I realize "wow... I managed to read an article for my thesis... and the mental noise is gone... and I remember what I read!"

This took me in a journey to learn about learning disabilities and neurodivergence. Resources such as @ADDitudeMag and @HowtoADHD were key to making me realize that I could potentially have an ADHD brain. And who knew, I did.

All went from there: What was my stressor? Was it my thesis? I realized that I was having strong issues reading articles that were not engaging to me. I felt "mental noise" all the time and my eyes just kept jumping all over the page not being able to read a paragraph.

During the pandemic I got a chance to stop for a moment and I started observing myself to try and understand why all of this was happening to me. I learned that I was procrastinating and that this is a common response to stressors.

I felt I was failing myself, my professors, those that believe in me and my relationship. Not a happy place to be in. My anxiety completely paralyzed me from getting anything done. I was in physical pain every day, in constant fear and generally going through insomnia.

Starting to fail really affected the view I had of myself and my capabilities. I felt I couldn't even complete the easiest of tasks. My self esteem really dipped. I started going through a very difficult moment in my life filled with paralyzing anxiety.

I never had issues in school. In fact, I always passed with honors. Once I started my https://t.co/AWeWyDMXde. degree in another country with a very different education system I started failing... Turns out I have ADHD and this is how many adults learn they have it too.

But if this becomes the popular way to discard oil, would its constant addition to landfills cause them to become a pollutant? Liquid frying oil can be recycled: Can the solid created by FryAway be recycled? Or does it become just another waste product contributing to GHG?

But I do have my concerns over what impacts would it have to dispose this in the trash. I suspect that the oil goes through a saponification process when mixed with the product. If it's soap, then the fx cause by landfill disposal should be negligible.
In fact, unlike other companies, they offer information about how FryAway helps to solve pollution problems caused by improper disposal of frying oil.

This is a general take on all products using these popular terms. Finding out about FryAway got me really interested in it and it is the reason why I am asking myself all these questions. This is not meant as an attack of this particular product.

Consumers should have clear understanding of what companies mean when they use terms like eco-friendly. Is it the carbon footprint of the product; production, packaging, transportation? Is it the way they degrade? Is it the problems they solve? Could they cause pollution?
My conversation prompt is the following: calling something eco-friendly, organic, vegan, surely makes products more attractive to buyers but should these labels be regulated?

One of the selling points of the product is that it turn the oil into a solid "organic waste". An organic waste is a plant or animal product that is biodegradable BUT it does not necessarily mean that it is eco-friendly or that it does not contribute to pollution.

This item claims that once the frying oil is turned to solid it can be disposed in the trash as an eco-friendly solution. I think this is a brilliant solution to prevent oil for going into the pipes. My question is: does this remain eco-friendly once it goes into the landfill? https://t.co/oHQLVCANPv
